%I A396953 #12 Jul 15 2026 18:24:28
%S A396953 1,8,35,118,353,996,2724,7320,19469,51464,135533,356122,934430,
%T A396953 2449752,6419007,16814034,44034041,115305800,301912016,790476616,
%U A396953 2069592857,5418423348,14185873605,37139515278,97233186458,254560876136,666450788219,1744793666830,4567933736849,11959013246604,31309115230428,81968347375032,214595951052485
%N A396953 Number of elements of word-length n in the reflection group of a seven-dimensional orthoscheme with distinct edge lengths.
%C A396953 The seven-dimensional orthoscheme (path simplex) is a simplex with eight vertices V_0, ..., V_7 whose consecutive edges V_0V_1, V_1V_2, ..., V_6V_7 are mutually perpendicular; here the seven edge lengths are distinct positive rationals. W is the reflection group generated by the reflections in the eight bounding facets, and a(n) is the number of distinct group elements of word-length n in these reflections.
%C A396953 Two facets are perpendicular exactly when they are non-consecutive, so W is the right-angled Coxeter group with the path Coxeter diagram P_8; its growth series is given by Steinberg's formula, which yields the generating function and recurrence below.
%C A396953 The growth depends only on the perpendicularity pattern, not on the edge lengths. For dimension >= 3 the geometric orbit count equals this abstract growth for any distinct edge lengths (proved in the linked paper, using that distinct edge lengths force the consecutive dihedral angles to be irrational multiples of Pi). The 2-dimensional analog is the right-triangle reflection group A396406, where the realization is not faithful, so its universality holds only to finite depth.
%H A396953 Vico Bonfioli, <a href="https://github.com/ElVec1o/pythagorean-reflection-sequence/blob/main/paper/journal/paper1b.pdf">Orthoscheme growth and Class C faithfulness</a>, 2026.
%H A396953 Vico Bonfioli, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.20370090">Data and proofs (Zenodo)</a>, doi:10.5281/zenodo.20370090, 2026.
%H A396953 <a href="/index/Rec#order_04">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (4,-3,-2,1).
%F A396953 G.f.: (1 + x)^4 / (1 - 4*x + 3*x^2 + 2*x^3 - x^4).
%F A396953 a(n) = 4*a(n-1) - 3*a(n-2) - 2*a(n-3) + a(n-4) for n >= 5.
%F A396953 a(n+1)/a(n) -> 1 + 2*cos(2*Pi/10) = (3 + sqrt(5))/2 = 2.6180339887..., the n = 7 case of r_n = 1 + 2*cos(2*Pi/(n+3)); it is the largest real root of x^4 - 4*x^3 + 3*x^2 + 2*x - 1.
%e A396953 a(1) = 8: the eight reflections in the eight bounding facets are the elements of word-length 1.
%t A396953 LinearRecurrence[{4, -3, -2, 1}, {1, 8, 35, 118, 353}, 33]
%o A396953 (Python)
%o A396953 def aseq(N):
%o A396953     s = [1, 8, 35, 118, 353]
%o A396953     while len(s) < N:
%o A396953         s.append(4*s[-1] - 3*s[-2] - 2*s[-3] + s[-4])
%o A396953     return s
%o A396953 print(aseq(33))
%o A396953 (PARI) Vec((1 + x)^4 / (1 - 4*x + 3*x^2 + 2*x^3 - x^4) + O(x^33))
%Y A396953 Cf. A397439 (3D), A397437 (4D), A396927 (5D), A397438 (6D), the lower-dimensional members of this orthoscheme family; A396406 (2D right-triangle analog); A008137 (3D all-equal-edges cube corner). Cf. A000045 (Fibonacci; the growth rate is the square of the golden ratio).
%K A396953 nonn,easy,new
